Updated guiding prompt for handbag generation (all bags are held in the hand):
Generate the handbag based on the input image and maintain its original proportions. Identify the type of bag from the description provided by the Florence model and adjust its size and positioning according to the following guidelines, with the requirement that all bags must be held in the character's hand:

Clutch or bag without straps:
Scale the bag to be small, with the length approximately equal to the length of the character's hand from wrist to fingertips (about 10-12 cm for an average adult), and the height about half of that length (around 5-6 cm).
The character should hold the bag directly in their hand, as if comfortably gripping a small object. The bag should not appear oversized or bulky in the grip.
Tote bag:
Scale the bag to be medium-sized, with the width approximately half of the character's torso width to look natural when held in the hand.
The handles should be proportional to the size of the bag, with a "drop length" (the distance from the top of the handle to the top of the bag) of about 10-15 cm for an average adult, so that the character can comfortably hold the bag in their hand without it dragging or appearing too large. The handles should be about 2-3 cm wide to fit naturally in the hand.
The bag should appear as if it is being held by the handles, with the body of the bag resting naturally against the character's side or leg.
Crossbody bag:
Scale the bag to be small to medium-sized, with the bag itself being about one-third of the character's torso width.
Since the bag must be held in the hand, adjust the strap to be shorter or draped in a way that allows the character to hold the bag by the strap or directly by the bag itself. The strap should be thin to medium thickness (about 1-3 cm wide).
The bag should appear as if it is being carried in the hand, with the strap either folded or hanging naturally.
Backpack:
Scale the bag to be small to medium-sized, so that it looks appropriate when held in the hand rather than worn on the back. The width should be about one-third to half of the character's torso.
The character should hold the backpack by one of the straps or by a top handle (if present). The straps should be proportional to the size of the bag, about 3-5 cm wide for an average adult.
The backpack should not appear oversized or cumbersome when held in the hand.
Shoulder bag:
Scale the bag to be medium-sized, with the width approximately half of the character's torso.
Adjust the strap to be shorter, so that the character can hold the bag by the strap or directly by the bag. The strap width should be about 2-4 cm to look natural when gripped.
The bag should appear as if it is being held in the hand, with the strap either looped or held along with the bag.
Satchel or messenger bag:
Scale the bag to be medium-sized, with the width approximately half of the character's torso.
Adjust the strap to be shorter or folded, so that the character can hold the bag by the strap or directly by the bag. The strap width should be about 2-4 cm for a natural grip.
The bag should look as if it is being comfortably held in the hand, with the strap not too long or unwieldy.
For other bag types:
Scale the bag so that the part held by the character (e.g., handles, straps, or the bag itself) fits naturally in their hand.
Adjust the rest of the bag proportionally, ensuring that any handles or straps are neither too large nor too small in relation to the character's hand and body.
General guidelines for handles and straps (when held in the hand):
Handle thickness: Handles should be proportional to the size of the bag and the character's hand. For smaller bags, handles can be about 1-2 cm wide, and for larger bags, up to 3 cm. They should appear easy to grip without dominating the bag's design.
Strap width: Straps should be wide enough to visually support the bag but not so wide that they look disproportionate when held (usually 1-3 cm for smaller bags, 2-4 cm for medium bags).
Natural grip: The character should appear to hold the bag comfortably in their hand, with handles or straps fitting naturally in the grip, as if carrying the bag effortlessly.
Proportionality: The bag should always be proportional to the character's hand and body, looking realistic and neither too large nor too small in the context of the image.
Ensure that the scale of the bag, especially the handles and straps, is adjusted to look realistic and natural when held in the character's hand, in relation to their body and the composition of the image.
